`IFormFile` buffers into memory by default — for large files you need to **read the raw request body stream** and write it to disk in chunks.

### Key changes

**1. Disable the default form body-size limit:**

```csharp
// Program.cs
builder.WebApplication.MapPost("/upload", HandleUpload)
    .DisableAntiforgery()
    .WithMetadata(new DisableRequestSizeLimitAttribute());

// Also raise Kestrel's limit in builder setup:
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024); // 2 GB
```

**2. Stream multipart sections to disk manually:**

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;

async Task<IResult> HandleUpload(HttpRequest request)
{
    if (!request.HasFormContentType)
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected a multipart request.");

    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(
        MediaTypeHeaderValue.Parse(request.ContentType).Boundary).Value;

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    MultipartSection? section;

    while ((section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync()) is not null)
    {
        if (!ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(
                section.ContentDisposition, out var disposition)
            || !disposition.IsFileDisposition())
            continue;

        // Sanitise the file name
        var fileName = Path.GetFileName(disposition.FileName.Value);
        var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

        // Stream directly to disk — only the buffer (80 KB default) is in memory
        await using var fileStream = File.Create(savePath);
        await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fileStream);
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete.");
}
```

### Why this works

| | `IFormFile` | `MultipartReader` |
|---|---|---|
| **Memory** | Entire file buffered | Only the read buffer (~80 KB) |
| **2 GB file** | OOM crash | Constant memory |
| **API** | Model-binding magic | Manual but full control |

### Don't forget

- **`DisableRequestSizeLimitAttribute`** — without it Kestrel rejects bodies > 30 MB.
- **Sanitize filenames** — `disposition.FileName` comes from the client; always use `Path.GetFileName()` and validate.
- If you're behind **IIS/Nginx**, raise their limits too (`maxAllowedContentLength` / `client_max_body_size`).
